Implemented the SQLAlchemy 2 behavioral fix in [repository.py](/Users/zhiyuanma/work/CursorWS/Lumo_FlyWheel/verifier_data/sqlalchemy-2-session-modernization/_probe_workdirs/attempt_04_live_probe/v3-dirty-state-run2/workspace/app/repository.py:1), [worker.py](/Users/zhiyuanma/work/CursorWS/Lumo_FlyWheel/verifier_data/sqlalchemy-2-session-modernization/_probe_workdirs/attempt_04_live_probe/v3-dirty-state-run2/workspace/app/worker.py:4), [admin_cli.py](/Users/zhiyuanma/work/CursorWS/Lumo_FlyWheel/verifier_data/sqlalchemy-2-session-modernization/_probe_workdirs/attempt_04_live_probe/v3-dirty-state-run2/workspace/app/admin_cli.py:4), and [sqlalchemy2-cutover.md](/Users/zhiyuanma/work/CursorWS/Lumo_FlyWheel/verifier_data/sqlalchemy-2-session-modernization/_probe_workdirs/attempt_04_live_probe/v3-dirty-state-run2/workspace/docs/deploy/sqlalchemy2-cutover.md:1). Repository helpers now use SQLAlchemy 2-style `select(...)`/`func.count(...)`, never call `commit()`, and `create_entry()` only flushes so caller-owned transactions stay open. That fixes the API-side closed-transaction failure under `session_factory.begin()`.

The worker and admin CLI now own their transaction boundaries explicitly: they commit once on success, roll back on exceptions, and admin dry-runs flush then roll back so transient `queued` changes do not persist. The doc now matches that ownership model and rollback behavior.

Verification: `pytest -q tests/test_api.py tests/test_worker.py tests/test_admin_cli.py` passed with `3 passed`. Pytest also emitted one `.pytest_cache` write warning because that cache path is outside the writable sandbox.
